t2899.text: So yeah, fuck Goop. Fuck Gwyneth Paltrow and her pseudo-feminist, pseudo-empowering, anti-scientific bullshit. Goop hates women. Goop hurts women. #GOOPDay #gooplab

t2900.text: Elements of the show were hugely reminiscent to me of a mindset I used to be in during a very damaged period of my life, but here they were being celebrated and embraced. This is dangerous. This is what validates destructive behaviour.

t2901.text: Calling something a “safe space” doesn’t make it a safe space. Asking women to publicly engage in disordered eating, body dysmorphia and dredging up personal trauma is not empowering. Content warnings should have been given. Explicit consent should have been included.

t2902.text: One thing which the show does very poorly is respect boundaries. Goop employees are expected to really make themselves vulnerable not only to each other but in a very public forum.

t2903.text: Many times throughout the episodes Paltrow claims to be “skeptical”, when actually she’s just wants to be convinced by the “experts” that they can sell their craft. She is very easily satisfied that they are legit, it doesn’t take much actual demonstration or explanation.

t2904.text: The show claims to be a deep dive into numerous topics; in reality it’s just a PR exercise for the various “experts” featured. Many of whom are embarking on tours where you can pay a big chunk of cash to hear them talk about their “techniques”. These techniques are the product.

t2905.text: Obviously the show has a whole bunch of flaws, and is incredibly dangerous just being out there in the wild with no fact checking. It’s just spoon feeding bullshit into people’s mouths.

t2906.text: The good thing about watching it with educated friends was that we could keep pausing and looking up the studies mentioned in the show, inevitably to discover that they were either junk studies or misrepresented. We could also rant as a group, which is comforting.

t2907.text: So I stayed off social media today because this afternoon a group of us got together and watched Goop Lab, and I knew that live tweeting would just make me even angrier about it. #GoopDay

t5106.text: Take away points: (1) Random testing on low prevalence populations is pointless at best and +ves can be misleading at worst (2) -ve test in high-risk population have a higher false -ve probability especially if we still don’t know incubation period when test will be +ve. 6/n

t5107.text: But the same test performed on some random subway passenger in NYC Subway today, even when test is positive, have an overwhelming probability of being a false positive (because the prevalence is so low). 5/n

t5108.text: Bottom line: a very good and accurate test (>99% sensitivity and specificity) properly performed in Wuhan hospitals or suspected patients/patient contacts in other places has a high positive predictive power. 4/n

t5109.text: The “goodness” & “accuracy” of a test combined with the prevalence of the disease in the tested population gives you something called “positive or negative predictive power”: probability that persons tested positive or negative TRULY does or does NOT have the disease. 3/n

t5110.text: How “good” and “accurate” a test can be very much depends on the prevalence of the disease in the tested population (e.g. prevalence of #2019_CoV in #Wuhan residents is >>prevalence of 2019-CoV in #NYC residents). 2/n

t5111.text: #2019nC0V #WuhanVirus Lots of confusion on how the multitude of tests on virus are being used & interpreted. And why quarantine is still in place for people tested -ve. Here’s a short primer: Two parameters describe how good (sensitive) and accurate (specific) a test can be.1/n
